post_text:
The USDA announced free breakfast and lunch for all students throughout the fall semester. This will start on Monday, Sept 14 at all three Keystone Schools. Free breakfast items include two grains, fruit, and a milk.
Lunch includes one meat/meat alternative (yogurt or cheese), a fruit, vegetable, grain, and milk. If you pack a lunch, and you need an individual item, such as a milk, it will need to be purchased for .50 . A la carte items are not included.

post_text:
Please note that due to precautions in place, we will not allow parents to enter the building. IF you are dropping something off for your high school student, please place it on the table in the vestibule area and be sure to have their name on the item. Text your student to let them know that the item is there and they will collect the item at their earliest convenience. At the present time we will not be delivering into a classroom.

If you are dropping off your student, you do not need to come into the building. Students at the high school must sign themselves in and obtain a pass. The same rules apply to early dismissals. Send in a note the day of the dismissal with the time they…

post_text:
We have had 938 responses to our survey with 75% of them choosing our Learning Model #1 Face-to-Face; and 25% choosing Learning Model #2 the Keystone Digital Academy. This survey will close Friday, August 7th so if you have not filled it out yet please do so before the end of the day on Friday.

We have had a number of people reach out to us with questions. If you have any questions, or have emailed us but have not heard back, please call or email us again and we will follow up with you.

For updated information on transportation within one mile of our school district please visit our website and click on: “Back to School Update Center” under the News section of our homepage. Then click on the Transportation section.

We are continuing to work on our plans for KeyCare and will be sharing them in the next day or two.

post_text:
A Message from Superintendent Dan White

It is hard to believe we are already in July! We hope you and your family are enjoying a healthy and relaxing summer vacation. As we look ahead to the 2020-2021 school year, and consider the guidance that comes out daily from organizations such as the Lorain County Health Department, the Ohio Department of Health and the Ohio Department of Education, we know that we must prepare for different scenarios considering the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic.

We greatly appreciate the over 1,000 survey responses we received on how remote learning went in the spring and also your preferences about returning in the fall. We have analyzed the results from both surveys and also surveyed our staff about their feelings. When combining the survey results of families and staff, over 80% of respondents want to return to school full time in the fall. Continue reading @
https://www.keystonelocalschools.org/about/news/1684539/superintendents-message

post_text:
KMS yearbooks are expected to arrive late on Thursday, 6/25. Parents can plan to pick-up their child’s yearbook on Tuesday, June 30th in the KMS car loop from 2-4 p.m. You will be asked to supply the name and current grade of your child to receive their book. If you are not sure if you purchased a book or not, please contact Mrs. Dillen or Mrs. Marxen before the pick up time and we can check for you.

For everyone’s safety, we ask that you wear a mask and stay in your car. Please do NOT send students on a bike or have them walk up to the school to get their books.

Anyone wishing to have someone else pick up their child’s copy, must contact kathryn.dillen@keystoneschools.org or kelly.marxen@…

Seniors - please plan to arrive at 5:30pm.

1. The parade begins at 6pm leaving from the old KMS/KHS school buildings at 301 Liberty Street.

2. We anticipate that the parade will reach our school streets around 6:45pm.

3. Our rain date will be May 29th - but let's hope it is not necessary!

post_text:
Attention Parents of Incoming Kindergartners/New KES Students
If you need to complete registration for an incoming kindergartner or another student new to Keystone Elementary, you can come in to the school office between 9am-3:00pm on the dates listed below.

Monday, May 11
Wednesday, May 13
Friday, May 15

Please have your child's birth certificate, immunization records, custody papers (if applicable), and two proofs of residency such as utility bill, mortgage statement, rental lease, voter registration, etc. The paperwork can be downloaded on our website under Keystone Elementary Forms. If you are unable to come in, please contact the KES office at 440-355-2328. https://www.keystonelocalschools.org/about/news/1679614/kes-new-students

post_text:
We want our seniors, their parents, and families to know how much we all care deeply about the importance of the milestones that accompany their senior year. We want to make these milestones as special as possible. Unfortunately, in following the Department of Health guidelines, we will not be able to have prom this year or the traditional graduation ceremony. We will do all we can to celebrate you in a manner that keeps everyone safe by following State guidelines. We are working on the plans for the celebration and truly do share your feelings of disappointment as our students’ senior year is a culmination of their secondary education. Our administrations, teachers, and support staff are committed to this effort and are currently working on a way to make this possible, while obeying State guidelines.
We will share these plans out to our Keystone Community as soon as possible.

post_text: The Ohio Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services (OhioMHAS) today joined with Governor Mike DeWine and RecoveryOhio to launch a new, toll-free Careline to provide emotional support for Ohioans who are experiencing stress, anxiety, fear, sadness and loneliness amid the COVID-19 pandemic. Ohioans may call 1-800-720-9616 to connect with trained counselors for 24/7 support. The Careline is staffed by credentialed counselors who have been trained to provide free, confidential support for a wide range of needs, including mental health concerns, substance use, problem gambling, and more. Individuals experiencing an acute crisis can still reach out to the Ohio Crisis Text Line (keyword 4HOPE to 741 741) or the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline (1-800-273-8255). More resources available @ https://www.keystonelocalschools.org/about/mental-health.

post_text:
Schedule requests have officially been entered into PowerSchool from the Course Selection guides that you have turned in. Please log into PowerSchool and check to make sure that your requests look accurate. In some cases, alternate courses were bumped as primary selections due to an insufficient amount of credits requested. Remember you are only allowed one study hall, so if you did not request enough courses, classes may have been added to your requests to meet your credit requirement. If you did not turn in a Course Selection Guide, then we built your schedule for you. Please review your course requests and email your counselor by Friday, April 10 if you have changes that you would like to make. We are going to begin building the master schedule, and we want to have as many accurate requests as possible. Contact information is below.
Alyssa Schwedt-Classes of 2022 & 2024
alyssa.schwedt@keystoneschools.org
440-355-2393

Meghann Gallo-Classes of 2021 & 2023
meghann.gallo@keystoneschools.org

text:
Schedule requests have officially been entered into PowerSchool from the Course Selection guides that you have turned in. Please log into PowerSchool and check to make sure that your requests look accurate. In some cases, alternate courses were bumped as primary selections due to an insufficient amount of credits requested. Remember you are only allowed one study hall, so if you did not request enough courses, classes may have been added to your requests to meet your credit requirement. If you did not turn in a Course Selection Guide, then we built your schedule for you. Please review your course requests and email your counselor by Friday, April 10 if you have changes that you would like to make. We are going to begin building the master schedule, and we want to have as many accurate requests as possible. Contact information is below.
Alyssa Schwedt-Classes of 2022 & 2024
alyssa.schwedt@keystoneschools.org
440-355-2393

Meghann Gallo-Classes of 2021 & 2023
meghann.gallo@keystoneschools.org
440-355-2394

post_text:
Per the Governor, all Ohio schools must close from Tuesday, March 17 through (tentatively) Friday, April 3. Our plan moving forward is below.

1. Keystone WILL be in session tomorrow, Friday, March 13.
2. Spring Break is March 16-20 as planned.
3. The week of March 23-27 will be treated as calamity days, and students will not be required to complete any assignments.
4. Beginning the week of March 30, teachers will provide lessons and assignments using Google Classroom. For those who do not have internet or device access, packets will be available in your child's school office.
5. Since we are using calamity days for the week of March 23 and remote learning for the week of March 30, no school days will be added to the end of the year.
Thank you for your patience as we monitor this fluid, unprecedented, and rapidly evolving situation.

post_text:
Like many schools, we have been planning in case we close for an extended period of time due to the Coronavirus. If this does happen, we will potentially provide lessons for students via the internet. If your student does not have access to the Internet, a laptop, or a computer, or some other device to complete lessons online, please call or email your child's building principal. We will use this data for planning purposes.

Keystone Schools continues to work closely with the Lorain County Public Health Department. For any questions you have regarding the Coronavirus or any other sickness you can visit their website at www.loraincountyhealth.com.

post_text: Senior Job Butcher had the honor of representing Keystone High School in the Ohio All-State Choir for the past three years. Job is the only Keystone Wildcat to have been chosen for this group three years in a row. post_text: We are seeking substitute teachers as well as substitute and full-time bus and van drivers. For substitute teacher positions, qualified applicants will hold a bachelor’s degree (in any field) and pass a FBI & BCI background check. Qualified applications for driver positions must be 21 years or older, have a clean driving record, and pass a FBI & BCI Background check. A CDL certification is preferred; however free training is also available. For either position, please apply in person or send in a resume to Keystone’s Board of Education Office, 580 Opportunity Way, LaGrange, Ohio.
